Quote: The genus <i>Chioonochloa (chion</i> = snow;<i>chloa</i> = grass) includes the snow tussocks, or tall tussocks - up to 2 metres high - that make up the grand, golden army that dominates our subalpine grasslands, furring the hills a tawny gold and forming a magnificent backdrop for beer and car commercials. ... [29] Snow tussocks, especially those tolerant of drier conditions, such as the narrow-leaved snow tussock (<i>C. rigida</i>), became widespread at lower altitudes.
